<h1><a href="../index.html">Breadcrumb</a></h1>

<p>There are numerous way to markup a bread crumb in HTML.  Is one better than the others?</p>
<p>The shortest a breadcrumb will be is 1 item (a link to home). The longest a
  breadcrumb will be is 3 items (a link to home, a parent category and a child category.
  We are not displaying the current page in the breadcrumb.</p>

<div class="live-example">
  <h2>1. Ordered List</h2>
  <ol class="breadcrumb">
    <li><a href="/">Home</a> &gt;</li>
    <li><a href="/debt/">Debt and borrowing</a> &gt;</li>
    <li><a href="/debt/problem">Mortgage and rent problems</a></li>
  </ol>

  <h2>2. Unordered list</h2>
  <ul class="breadcrumb">
    <li><a href="/">Home</a> &gt;</li>
    <li><a href="/debt/">Debt and borrowing</a> &gt;</li>
    <li><a href="/debt/problem">Mortgage and rent problems</a></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>3. Paragraph </h2>
  <p><a href="/">Home</a> &gt;
    <a href="/debt/">Debt and borrowing</a> &gt;
    <a href="/debt/problem">Mortgage and rent problems</a>
  </p>


  <h2>4. Is it helpful to wrap the breadcrumb in a nav element and give it a label of breadcrumb?</h2>
  <nav role="navigation" aria-label="breadcrumb">
    <p><a href="/">Home</a> &gt;
      <a href="/debt/">Debt and borrowing</a> &gt;
      <a href="/debt/problem">Mortgage and rent problems</a>
    </p>
  </nav>

